John Edward: Without language skills, global citizenship is not possible.
Scotland's independent schools are maintaining excellent academic results and this trend continues in 2018 with another year of exceptional test results, further reinforcing individual and collective achievements in sports, the arts, music and other social activities.
With over 30 000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare students for further and higher education, their dream careers and their place in the world as global citizens.
As the education sector can design and implement tailored school curricula, we still see modern languages as a popular and sought-after choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "When you speak to a man in a language he understands, you are speaking to his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you are speaking to his heart.
It's a powerful reminder that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we can't rely on English alone.
And we see from this year's test scores that languages are at the top of the table with the highest average grades among independent schools.
Overall, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages scored the highest A's.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved the highest A grades in Mandarin Chinese, 72 percent in German, 69 percent in French, and 63 percent in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as a basic skill which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages as electives are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in both independent and non-selective schools.
A 2014 UK Employment and Skills Commission survey found that 17% of the reasons cited by employers as problems with filling jobs were insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising job opportunities arise that require languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career path a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with this lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75 percent could not speak any foreign language sufficiently to be able to converse fluently, with French being the only language where the number of people reached double-digit percentages (15 percent).
That's why it's important for children today to invest in language learning.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will vary according to the languages taught.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important to the UK in terms of the future in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, independent schools will always offer a choice of languages and will teach him or her by experts in the field.
Scotland's independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At present, it is undeniable that in a global business environment, languages remain fundamental to a country's future, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be called international communication skills.
Independent schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
