North Korea will not unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions had deepened mistrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual general assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "substantial countermeasures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"But we don't see any corresponding reaction from the US", he added.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there can be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, it is out of the question that we should be the first to unilaterally disarm".
While Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, whereby North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his position was crucial in that he did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula while Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea has sought to achieve a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The US insists on nuclear disarmament first and raises tensions through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion and even by opposing the declaration of an end to the war", Ri said.
The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is an illusion of people who know nothing about us.
The problem is that the continuing sanctions are deepening our mistrust.
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim Jong Un and Trump, which the US president told the United Nations earlier this week.
However, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the other side of the nuclear disarmament issue were South Korea instead of the United States, the disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a dead end".
Yet Ri's tone of speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korean missile strikes on US soil were inevitable after President Trump called Kim a "suicide bomber".
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, sang at the UN praising Kim for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions must remain until North Korea was "denuclearized".
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this, saying it didn't matter if it took two, three years or five months.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
But US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of the Security Council's sanctions must continue strictly and without exception until we achieve complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament".
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit didn't go well.
In July, he left Pyongyang with a statement that progress had been made, but a few hours later, North Korea condemned him for making "gangster demands".
North Korea has pledged at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile test site and nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate action".
