Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
The goal of this year's new course at Harvard University is to get all students more sleep in an effort to counter the growing trend of studying all night with the help of caffeine.
Researchers have found that students at the world's leading university are often helpless when it comes to the very basics of taking care of their health.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Clinic, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course by a lecture he gave on sleep deprivation and its impact on learning.
At the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why do I have to know about this until now, in my senior year?"
"She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, explains the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance while improving overall health.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said that the university decided to open the course after discovering that students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the workweek.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section shows a picture of a boarding room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books and learn about the effects of caffeine, light, and how lack of sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of a regular sleep routine.
In the next section, participants will learn how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons further encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this won't change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know  just as everyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes", added Professor Czeisler.
There's still a culture where students are proud to be able to study all night, he says, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation has become a growing problem.
Providing adequate, quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even against weight gain, because sleep deficit puts the brain in a starvation mode, so they feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, was helping Professor Czeisler design a course after attending one of his seminars last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to try to push the course to the university level.
He hopes that in the next step, it will be possible to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar programme of study before embarking on a demanding study.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set their alarm clock for both bedtime and wake-up time, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
