Fishing and agriculture are the main mainstays of the economy of Central Sulawesi, especially the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, the cities of Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit the western part of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia lies seismically within the Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly struck by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake off the west coast of Aceh province in Indonesia's northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26 that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck the southern part of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake occurred near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck one of the islands of Mentawai, off Sumatra, triggering a tsunami as high as 33 feet [10 m] that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A weak earthquake hit the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation caused by the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people died as a result of the collapse of buildings.
2018: Large earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
