Federal prosecutors are seeking a rare death sentence for a suspect in a terrorist attack in New York City .
Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Sayful Saipov, suspected of the New York terror attack that killed eight people - a rare punishment not imposed for a federal crime in the state since 1953.
On October 31st, 30-year-old Saipov allegedly used a rented Home Depot truck to carry out an attack on a bike path along the West Side Highway in lower Manhattan by crashing pedestrians and a cyclist on the trail.
According to the notice of commencement of the death penalty proceedings filed in the Southern District of New York, if prosecutors want to get the death penalty, they'll have to prove that Saipov "intentionally" killed eight victims and "intentionally" caused serious injury.
Both of these charges are punishable by death, according to the court document.
A few weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury indicted Saipov on 22 counts, including eight counts of murder with the intent to blackmail, which are typically used by federal prosecutors in organized crime cases, and one count of assault and destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack required "substantial planning and cold-blooded thought", prosecutors said, and the manner in which Saipov carried it out was described as "horrible, cruel and perverse".
'Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov has caused injury, harm and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erli, Hernán Ferruchi, Hernán Diego Mendoza and Alejandra Damián Pagnucca,' the report of the intention states.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It's been a decade since the Southern District of New York last passed the death penalty.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of the murder of two drug dealers, but in September 2009 was finally sentenced to life in prison.
The last execution was carried out in a federal case in New York in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple who had been executed after being convicted of conspiracy and espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, showed a lack of conscience in the days and months following the attack, according to court documents.
He told investigators he felt good about what he did, police said.
According to the prosecution, Saipov said he was inspired to carry out the attack by watching ISIS videos on his phone.
Police said he also requested an ISIS flag be displayed in his hospital room.
He pleaded not guilty to 22 counts of the indictment.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders representing Saipov, said they were obviously disappointed with the prosecution's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty instead of a guilty plea and life in prison without the possibility of parole only prolongs the trauma of these events for all involved", Patton said.
